# Extraction-accuracy golden set for the call -> CRM stage (Ch 22).
#
# Each row is one call transcript and the CRM fields the workflow should END UP WRITING after the
# conservative-write gate (NOT the raw extraction). That is the contract that matters: the forecast
# is only as good as what actually lands in the CRM. The candidate under test is
# `evals.harness.extract_candidate`, which runs the real `process_call` and returns its `applied`
# (written) fields; the grader is `evals.harness.FieldsMatch`, which scores field-by-field with
# partial credit so a near-miss is visible, not a flat fail.
#
# Tags slice the score: `extraction` (did we get the field values right?), `conservative-write`
# (did the low-confidence/absent fields get withheld, not guessed?), and a stage/account label.
#
# The KEY conservative-write case is `acme-amount-hedged`: the buyer named ~$50k but hedged on
# finance sign-off, so `amount` MUST be flagged (withheld), not written — bad data in the forecast
# is worse than missing data.
